BookShelf and Users Analytics based Segmentation

Date: 11th December, 2024

Dataset: Online Books and Consumers Demographics Dataset from Amazon

Aim: The aim of this project is to develop an advanced customer segmentation system for a book company using data-driven clustering techniques. By analyzing user behavior, preferences, and purchase history, the system will identify distinct customer segments, enabling personalized marketing, targeted recommendations, and optimized customer engagement strategies. This segmentation will help the company better understand its diverse readership, enhance user experiences, and drive growth by tailoring products and services to specific customer needs and behaviors.

start_date = pd.to_datetime('2022-11-01')
end_date = pd.to_datetime('2024-06-30')

# Number of rows in the dataset
num_rows = len(merged_data)  # Replace 'merged_data' with your DataFrame name

# Generate random timestamps using numpy.uniform
random_timestamps = np.random.uniform(start_date.timestamp(), end_date.timestamp(), num_rows)

# Convert timestamps back to datetime
random_dates = pd.to_datetime(random_timestamps, unit='s')

# Add the random dates as a new column
merged_data['Random_Date'] = random_dates

The Outliers in the dataset are removed.

In[331]:
for feature in sampled_data.columns:
    if sampled_data[feature].dtype in ['float64', 'int64']:
        Q1 = sampled_data[feature].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = sampled_data[feature].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5*IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
        sampled_data = sampled_data[
            (sampled_data[feature] >= lower_bound) & (sampled_data[feature] <= upper_bound)
        ]

# Optional: Fill NaN values after handling outliers
# features = sampled_data.fillna(sampled_data.median())

For finding an optimized number of clusters for the dataset, Elbow method is used.

In[336]:
distortions = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(scaled_features)
    distortions.append(kmeans.inertia_)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(range(1, 11), distortions, marker='o')
plt.title('Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Distortion')
plt.show()

From the above Graph, the ideal number of clusters formed in this combination of features is 6.

In[337]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
In[338]:
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=6, random_state=42)  # Choose 5 clusters
clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(scaled_features)

Another Dataset is made named cluster_stats which consists of grouping the individual clusters and consists of columns like:

  • Cluster
  • Average Age
  • Minimum Age
  • Maximum Age
  • Location
  • Average Rating
  • Median Rating
  • Minimum Rating
  • Maximum Rating
  • Book Titles
In[341]:
#.Perform.the aggregation as.before
cluster_stats = features.groupby('Cluster').agg({
    'Age': ['mean', 'min', 'max' ],
    'Location': lambda x: list(x.unique()),
    'Book-Rating': ['mean', 'median', 'min', 'max' ],
    'Book-Title': lambda x: list(x.unique()) #Aggregating.book.titles.as.a.list
}).reset_index()

#.Flatten.the.multi-level.columns
cluster_stats.columns = ['_'.join(col).strip() for col in cluster_stats.columns.values]

#.Rename.the. columns.for.better.readability
cluster_stats.columns = ['Cluster',
                         'Avg_Age', 'Min_Age', 'Max_Age',
                         'Location',
                         'Avg_Rating', 'Median_Rating', 'Min_Rating', 'Max_Rating',
                         'Book_Titles']

The encoded Book Title are mapped to the values in book_title_to_original for fetching the Original Titles.

In[342]:
cluster_stats['Book_Titles'] = cluster_stats['Book_Titles'].apply(
    lambda x: [book_title_to_original.get(book_id, "Unknown Title") for book_id in x] if isinstance(x, list) else book_title_to_original.get(x, "Unknown Title")
)

Similarly, the encoded Locations are mapped to the values in location_to_original for fetching the Original Locations.

In[343]:
cluster_stats['Location'] = cluster_stats['Location'].apply(
    lambda x: [location_to_original.get(location, "Unknown Title") for location in x] if isinstance(x, list) else location_to_original.get(x, "Unknown Title")
)

  • Publisher

    Frequency=('ISBN', 'count'), #.Count.of.books.interacted.with
    Average_Rating=('Book-Rating', 'mean'),#Average.rating.given.bythe.user.#Average.age.(if.needed)
    Total_Revenue_Earned = ('Price','sum' )
).reset_index()

The Outliers are removed to get General Category of Books and Authors

In[353]:
for feature in book_stats.columns:
    if book_stats[feature].dtype in ['float64', 'int64']:
        Q1 = book_stats[feature].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = book_stats[feature].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5*IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
        book_stats = book_stats[
            (book_stats[feature] >= lower_bound) & (book_stats[feature] <= upper_bound) 
        ]

In[383]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture

# Fit GMM for different numbers of components (clusters)
n_components_range = range(1, 11)  # Try 1 to 10 clusters
aic_scores = []
bic_scores = []

for n in n_components_range:
    gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=n)
    gmm.fit(features)  # Assuming `features` is your data
    aic_scores.append(gmm.aic(features))
    bic_scores.append(gmm.bic(features))

# Plot the AIC and BIC scores to find the "elbow"
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(n_components_range, aic_scores, label='AIC', color='blue', marker='o')
plt.plot(n_components_range, bic_scores, label='BIC', color='red', marker='x')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Score')
plt.title('AIC and BIC Scores for Different Cluster Numbers')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

As per the AIC and BIC Scores, the ideal number for clustering is 8.

In[384]:
from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture
